05917nam a22007335i 9780824860288DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20112011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248602887 a10.1515/97808248602882doi  a(DE-B1597)484431  a(OCoLC)794925359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPR9484.3b.J64 2011 7aLIT0080202bisacsh04a820.9/9541 aJohnson, Alan G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut of Bounds :bAnglo-Indian Literature and the Geography of Displacement /cAlan G. Johnson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWriting Past Colonialism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Colonial Space, Anglo-Indian Perspectives -- tChapter 1. “I Want to Send India to England”: The Aesthetics of Landscape and the Colonial Home -- tChapter 2. Hills Kinder Than Plains? Kipling’s Monstrous Hill Station -- tChapter 3. “Out of Bounds”: Clubs, Cantonments, Plains -- tChapter 4. Savage City: Locating Colonial Modernity -- tChapter 5. Medical Topography in Flora Annie Steel’s On the Face of the Waters -- tChapter 6. The Engineers′ Revenge, the Age of Kali: Kipling’s Bridges and the End of Jungles -- tChapter 7. Man-Eaters of Kumaon and Jim Corbett’s Jungle Idiom -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOut of Bounds focuses on the crucial role that conceptions of iconic colonial Indian spaces—jungles, cantonments, cities, hill stations, bazaars, clubs—played in the literary and social production of British India. Author Alan Johnson illuminates the geographical, rhetorical, and ideological underpinnings of such depictions and, from this, argues that these spaces operated as powerful motifs in the acculturation of Anglo-India. He shows that the bicultural, intrinsically ambivalent outlook of Anglo-Indian writers is acutely sensitive to spatial motifs that, insofar as these condition the idea of home and homelessness, alternately support and subvert conventional colonial perspectives.Colonial spatial motifs not only informed European representations of India, but also shaped important aesthetic notions of the period, such as the sublime. This book also explains how and why Europeans’ rhetorical and visual depictions of the Indian subcontinent, whether ostensibly administrative, scientific, or aesthetic, constituted a primary means of memorializing Empire, creating an idiom that postcolonial India continues to use in certain ways. Consequently, Johnson examines specific motifs of Anglo-Indian cultural remembrance, such as the hunting memoir, hill station life, and the Mutiny, all of which facilitated the mythic iconography of the Raj. He bases his work on the premise that spatiality (the physical as well as social conceptualization of space) is a vital component of the mythos of colonial life and that the study of spatiality is too often a subset of a focus on temporality.Johnson reads canonical and lesser-known fiction, memoirs, and travelogues alongside colonial archival documents to identify shared spatial motifs and idioms that were common to the period. Although he discusses colonial works, he focuses primarily on the writings of Anglo-Indians such as Rudyard Kipling, John Masters, Jim Corbett, and Flora Annie Steel to demonstrate how conventions of spatial identity were rhetorically maintained—and continually compromised. All of these considerations amplify this book’s focus on the porosity of boundaries in literatures of the colony and of the nation.Out of Bounds will be of interest to not only postcolonial literary scholars, but also scholars and students in interdisciplinary nineteenth-century studies, South Asian cultural history, cultural anthropology, women’s studies, and sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnglo-Indian literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAnglo-Indian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aColonies in literature. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aSpace in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Indic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486028840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824860288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824860288.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK